		<div id="comment_body_32873420"><p>State-based (and territory-backed) currencies existed in the United States well into the 19th Century and even partly into the 20th Century in the case of the Alaskan Gold Rush.  It was something directly tied to a lack of liquidity and the fact that the economies of those regions needed an extra jump start to get something going.</p><p>Usually state-backed currencies in the 19th Century had a one to one relationship with the U.S. Dollar, so it wasn't as big of a deal.  The Federal Reserve wasn't established until<span class="substr"> </span></p></div>
	</div>

